            {
                "s2_paper_id": "9fb9e4f31d93b53e9d54f08136c71037c57def28",
                "title": "Trityl OXO71 Pharmacokinetics and Distribution in Rhesus Macaques",
                "year": 2025,
                "venue": "Magnetic Resonance in Medicine",
                "citation_count": 0,
                "reference_count": 25,
                "abstract": "Electron paramagnetic resonance oxygen imaging (EPROI) techniques have the ability to quantify the partial pressure of oxygen (pO2), in vivo, through quantitative measurement of T1e maps of the trityl radical, OXO71. OXO71\u2010based EPROI has seen several applications in small animal imaging studies, but translation to humans will benefit from optimization of EPROI using large animal subjects that are anatomically and physiologically similar to humans. The goal of this study was to characterize pharmacokinetics and tissue distribution following an intravenous administration of OXO71 in rhesus macaques.",
